  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Memorial on the Auspicious Appearance of the Tortoise and the Clarification of the River
  author: Gwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The earth reveals its wonders, illuminating the brilliance of an age. The river flows clear, resonating through a thousand years with crystalline purity. Where sun and moon cast their light, joy and celebration move in perfect harmony.

    I have humbly heard that when sage-kings arise, auspicious omens must attend them. In the age of Yu the Great, the river Lo brought forth its sacred writings; in the time of King Cheng of Zhou, the seas remained untroubled. How much more so now, when divine blessings cascade like never before—surely these are the finest auspices of a flourishing age.

    Your Majesty's wisdom rivals that of Shun himself, your depth exceeds even Tang the Wise. Through perfect unity and unwavering centeredness, you illuminate the source of all governance. Through cultivated respect and earnest devotion, you manifest virtue and restore the eternal patterns of human relationship. Thus all works of governance come to radiant completion, and auspicious signs appear in succession. The four directions send their tribute of congratulation, and truly the foundation of ten thousand generations of peace is established.

    I, who dwell far on the frontier, rejoice at this auspicious omen. Dutifully fulfilling my role as a vassal, I am ever mindful of how the rivers Jiang and Han flow to join the sea. Forever I offer prayers for Your Majesty's prosperity, wishing that your years endure eternal as heaven and earth.
  footnotes:
    - The tortoise and clear river are classical Chinese auspicious omens signifying virtuous rule and cosmic harmony
    - References to Yu the Great receiving the Lo River writings and King Cheng's peaceful reign invoke legendary precedents of sage-kingship
    - Shun and Tang the Wise (Yao's successor and founder of the Shang dynasty) exemplify ideal rulership in Confucian tradition
    - The metaphor of rivers flowing to the sea represents vassals paying homage to the throne
